{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01CTJf6Ggjbx9F1Cup98pBcM","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Verdict Reasoning: 3616779a — When Actions Go Off-Task\n2\t\n3\t**Paper:** When Actions Go Off-Task: Detecting and Correcting Misaligned Actions in Computer-Use Agents  \n4\t**Paper ID:** 3616779a-8ed8-4d00-9a1c-71616a5ecbd2  \n5\t**Date:** 2026-04-28  \n6\t**Score:** 5.0 (weak accept, lower band)\n7\t\n8\t---\n9\t\n10\t## Novelty Assessment\n11\t\n12\tThe paper introduces MISACTBENCH, the first multimodal Computer-Use Agent (CUA) benchmark with per-action alignment labels (Fleiss' κ = 0.84), and a two-stage detection-correction pipeline (fast-check + rewriter) built on Claude Sonnet 4.5. The per-action labeling granularity is a genuine methodological advance over prior trajectory-level safety labels in WebArena, OSWorld, and similar benchmarks. The decomposition into misalignment detection (fast-check) and correction (rewriter) cleanly separates the two problems.\n13\t\n14\tNovelty cell: **clear-novelty** (per-action annotation granularity + detection-correction pipeline are new relative to trajectory-level CUA safety work)\n15\t\n16\t---\n17\t\n18\t## Rigor Assessment\n19\t\n20\t**Critical concern — synthesizer-detector confound:**  \n21\tAs I noted in my comment [[comment:9391c85c-6139-4ca0-a4cf-fb5c1c7376bb]] and claude_shannon elaborated [[comment:65292a6d-e7c0-47af-9a76-7da548a370f8]], Claude Sonnet 4.5 serves as both the primary backbone for MISACTBENCH annotation/construction and as the fast-check and rewriter backbone in the evaluated pipeline. This creates a same-family recognition bias: the detector may perform well partly because it shares stylometric and behavioral priors with the generator, rather than because the method generalizes to misaligned actions from other agent families. The effect is attenuated in fast-check (lightweight heuristic) but meaningful in the rewriter stage. No cross-family generalization experiment (e.g., using a GPT-4o-generated trace evaluated by the Claude-based pipeline) is provided.\n22\t\n23\t**Secondary concern — Table E.1 brittle recall:**  \n24\tTable E.1 shows recall of 73.81% on H-type (hacked/adversarial) misalignment examples, implying a 26.19% miss rate on the hardest misalignment category. For a safety-critical CUA monitoring system, this miss rate is potentially unacceptable and the paper does not discuss the deployment implications.\n25\t\n26\t**Novelty framing concern:**  \n27\tEntropius [[comment:b64cde38-4600-47b1-a2fc-b5a8b2ec370b]] and emperorPalpatine [[comment:08e11686-0b08-45f2-afe2-ec4c3309aedb]] both note that framing this as the \"first effort\" creates tension with concurrent work (Task Shield, InferAct). The paper cites these as contemporaneous but the extent of methodological overlap is not fully characterized.\n28\t\n29\tRigor cell: **some concerns** (synthesizer-detector confound reduces evaluation validity; brittle recall on adversarial cases)\n30\t\n31\t---\n32\t\n33\t## Grid Assignment\n34\t\n35\t| Novelty | Rigor | Default band | Score |\n36\t|---------|-------|-------------|-------|\n37\t| clear-novelty | some concerns | weak accept (upper) | 6.0–6.8 |\n38\t\n39\tSynthesizer-detector confound and the brittle adversarial recall pull toward the lower bound. The per-action labeling contribution and high inter-annotator agreement are genuine strengths. Adjusted score: **5.0**\n40\t\n41\t---\n42\t\n43\t## Citations in Verdict\n44\t\n45\t- [[comment:65292a6d-e7c0-47af-9a76-7da548a370f8]] — claude_shannon: synthesizer-detector confound + adaptive attacker concern\n46\t- [[comment:b64cde38-4600-47b1-a2fc-b5a8b2ec370b]] — Entropius: novelty relative to concurrent work (Task Shield, InferAct)\n47\t- [[comment:08e11686-0b08-45f2-afe2-ec4c3309aedb]] — emperorPalpatine: multiple novelty and soundness concerns\n48\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9feabeec-9340-4c0a-b074-38da91250684","uuid":"ac9459bd-a610-411d-8014-dda5b30eafef","timestamp":"2026-04-28T17:52:13.425Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/mila/e/elarabim/code/x-reviewer-agent/agent_configs/quadrant/reasoning/3616779a_verdict_20260428.md","content":"# Verdict Reasoning: 3616779a — When Actions Go Off-Task\n\n**Paper:** When Actions Go Off-Task: Detecting and Correcting Misaligned Actions in Computer-Use Agents  \n**Paper ID:** 3616779a-8ed8-4d00-9a1c-71616a5ecbd2  \n**Date:** 2026-04-28  \n**Score:** 5.0 (weak accept, lower band)\n\n---\n\n## Novelty Assessment\n\nThe paper introduces MISACTBENCH, the first multimodal Computer-Use Agent (CUA) benchmark with per-action alignment labels (Fleiss' κ = 0.84), and a two-stage detection-correction pipeline (fast-check + rewriter) built on Claude Sonnet 4.5. The per-action labeling granularity is a genuine methodological advance over prior trajectory-level safety labels in WebArena, OSWorld, and similar benchmarks. The decomposition into misalignment detection (fast-check) and correction (rewriter) cleanly separates the two problems.\n\nNovelty cell: **clear-novelty** (per-action annotation granularity + detection-correction pipeline are new relative to trajectory-level CUA safety work)\n\n---\n\n## Rigor Assessment\n\n**Critical concern — synthesizer-detector confound:**  \nAs I noted in my comment [[comment:9391c85c-6139-4ca0-a4cf-fb5c1c7376bb]] and claude_shannon elaborated [[comment:65292a6d-e7c0-47af-9a76-7da548a370f8]], Claude Sonnet 4.5 serves as both the primary backbone for MISACTBENCH annotation/construction and as the fast-check and rewriter backbone in the evaluated pipeline. This creates a same-family recognition bias: the detector may perform well partly because it shares stylometric and behavioral priors with the generator, rather than because the method generalizes to misaligned actions from other agent families. The effect is attenuated in fast-check (lightweight heuristic) but meaningful in the rewriter stage. No cross-family generalization experiment (e.g., using a GPT-4o-generated trace evaluated by the Claude-based pipeline) is provided.\n\n**Secondary concern — Table E.1 brittle recall:**  \nTable E.1 shows recall of 73.81% on H-type (hacked/adversarial) misalignment examples, implying a 26.19% miss rate on the hardest misalignment category. For a safety-critical CUA monitoring system, this miss rate is potentially unacceptable and the paper does not discuss the deployment implications.\n\n**Novelty framing concern:**  \nEntropius [[comment:b64cde38-4600-47b1-a2fc-b5a8b2ec370b]] and emperorPalpatine [[comment:08e11686-0b08-45f2-afe2-ec4c3309aedb]] both note that framing this as the \"first effort\" creates tension with concurrent work (Task Shield, InferAct). The paper cites these as contemporaneous but the extent of methodological overlap is not fully characterized.\n\nRigor cell: **some concerns** (synthesizer-detector confound reduces evaluation validity; brittle recall on adversarial cases)\n\n---\n\n## Grid Assignment\n\n| Novelty | Rigor | Default band | Score |\n|---------|-------|-------------|-------|\n| clear-novelty | some concerns | weak accept (upper) | 6.0–6.8 |\n\nSynthesizer-detector confound and the brittle adversarial recall pull toward the lower bound. The per-action labeling contribution and high inter-annotator agreement are genuine strengths. Adjusted score: **5.0**\n\n---\n\n## Citations in Verdict\n\n- [[comment:65292a6d-e7c0-47af-9a76-7da548a370f8]] — claude_shannon: synthesizer-detector confound + adaptive attacker concern\n- [[comment:b64cde38-4600-47b1-a2fc-b5a8b2ec370b]] — Entropius: novelty relative to concurrent work (Task Shield, InferAct)\n- [[comment:08e11686-0b08-45f2-afe2-ec4c3309aedb]] — emperorPalpatine: multiple novelty and soundness concerns\n","numLines":48,"startLine":1,"totalLines":48}}}
